observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management adopt the procedural flow in the acceptance, issuance, and recording of inventories pursuant to the afore-cited laws and regulations. The following are the recommended changes in the procedures:
a. The inspection of deliveries of supplies and materials purchased shall be conducted by the CGSO and shall be accepted in the Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR). The custody of the inventory items shall be the responsibility of the CGSO until issuance thereof to the Requesting Party/Department;
b. A Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) (numbered based on RIS logbook) shall be prepared in three copies to turn over the responsibility of the supplies and materials from the CGSO to the Requesting Offices/Department upon its release, distributed as follows:
Copy 1- Accounting
Copy 2- Requesting Party/Department
Copy 3- File Copy of CGSO;
c. The designated Stock Custodians of the other supplies and materials shall maintain Stock Cards to record the receipt and issuances of the inventories in their custody. The CGSO shall likewise maintain the stock cards of the supplies in their custody;
d. For inventory items for distribution, the Requesting Party/Department shall be responsible for the proper distribution thereof to the barangays and/or client-beneficiaries. A sub-RIS in four copies shall be prepared for the request for issuance of supplies and materials, distributed as follows:
Copy 1- Accounting
Copy 2- Requesting Party
Copy 3- File Copy of CGSO
Copy 4- File copy of Requesting Office/Department;
e. The Requesting Office/Department shall number the sub-RIS based on a sub-RIS Logbook maintained for the purpose. The sub-RIS Logbook shall have the following column headings: sub-RIS No., Date, Description and Quantity of ‘Supplies and Materials’ (header name may be changed depending on the applicable term for each department) to be Issued, Name of Requesting Party, Position/Designation, Official Station or Address, and Signature;
f. After properly accomplishing and signing the sub-RIS, the Requesting Office/Department shall issue the supplies to the barangay officials/clients/end-users authorized to receive the same;
g. The Requesting Office/Department shall submit to the CGSO, every week or as necessary, the 1st and 3rd copies of the sub-RIS. The CGSO shall promptly prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) based on the RIS and sub-RIS, which shall be submitted to the City Accountant for recording;
h. The City Accountant shall prepare a JEV to record the proper inventory expense based on the SSMI received from the CGSO. She shall prepare and maintain a complete and updated Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) for each item of inventory and utilize the same to compute the cost of supplies issued, applying the moving average method;
i. The Requesting Office/Department shall require all requesting parties in the sub-RIS to submit the Relief Distribution Lists/ Liquidation Sheets within 15 days after the distribution of the supplies to the beneficiaries. There shall be a regular monitoring of the submission thereof and follow- up with the concerned barangays/recipients who failed to submit the Relief Distribution Lists/ Liquidation Sheets;
j. The Requesting Party/Department shall prepare and submit the liquidation report, once the Relief Distribution Lists/ Liquidation Sheets are complete, to the City Accountant for submission to the Auditor and to monitor the liquidation; and
k. The City Accountant and the CGSO shall regularly reconcile their respective records to determine any errors in the recording of inventory procurement and issuances.
Henceforth, we recommended that Management come up with internal control procedures that will ensure proper handling of inventories to prevent or minimize the risk of loss and misuse such as maintaining complete and updated Stock Cards (SC) to account for the receipts, issuances, and balances of each inventory item in every department/office and look into the probability for provision of a warehouse or stockroom with sufficient space to store the operational requirements of the LGU for supplies and materials.
We likewise recommended that Management direct the Stock Custodians to promptly submit to the accounting office the SSMI, RIS, and other necessary attachments for the proper recording of the expenses in the books of the LGU.

We reiterated our recommendation that Local Chief Executive requires the Municipal Accountant to: 

strictly monitor the submission of the liquidation reports;

submit the required report and supporting documents on the liquidation of various cash advances amounting to ₱14,820,569.46;

strictly comply with the provision of the above-mentioned circulars.

We recommended that the LCE require the Municipal Accountant to identify 	the status and establish the correct balance of the Due to NGAs account for each SA and 	thereafter: 

return/refund to the concerned SA the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof;  

revert to the Government Equity the balances of the fund transfers in the nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention of the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual budgeting, accounting and auditing laws, rules and regulations; 

 retain special purpose funds; or 

clean the books of accounts in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023 to present fairly the Liability account in the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Management:

Require the General Services Officer (GSO) to prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) based on the Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS), at least on a monthly basis, to be submitted to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record issuances of inventories from stock;

Further, the GSO prepare and maintain stock cards for each type of inventory, with complete information/data to facilitate verification receipts, issuances and balances of inventories on hand; 

Require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records, at least, on a quarterly basis to ensure accuracy of the balances of the inventory accounts;

Provide an adequate stockroom to safely keep all procured stocks of the LGU so that inventories are only issued to end-users when needed; and 

Subject to availability of funds, augment the manpower of the GSO so that there will be personnel charged with the recording, monitoring, and safekeeping of the inventories of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management require the:

Accounting Office to exert effort in tracing relevant information pertaining to the dormant receivable and payable accounts to establish the validity and accuracy of the account balances;

Treasurer’s Office to enforce settlement or collection of claims;  

Accounting Office to prepare the aging of receivables and payables;and

Accounting Office to request for write-off of dormant accounts where settlement could no longer be ascertained in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management require the:

Direct the GSO to complete the reconciliation of RPCPPE and PPE account balance;

Require the Inventory Committee to complete the “One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006, so that only serviceable and existing items at year-end are reported as PPE to allow fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the year-end financial statements;  

Order the Inventory team to identify if the variances are non-existing/missing or unrecorded PPE as well as the persons accountable for proper disposition based on Sections 7 to 9 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;

Direct the GSO to reclassify the previously classified PPE items costing below ₱50,000.00 which are still in their custody to the appropriate semi-expendable property account, prepare ICS for semi-expandable property acquired in CY 2022 onwards, and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property; and

Designate a personnel/team which shall be responsible for securing the land titles of the 26 lots and likewise appropriate funds to cover its cost.

(19) We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
a. to conduct risk assessment; 
b. to identify critical processes and functions; 
c. to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
d. to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
e. to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
f. to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
(20) Further, we recommended that members of the working group be capacitated by allowing them to attend seminars/trainings on the formulation of the PSCP.

We reiterated prior years’ recommendations that Management:

Reconstitute the Inventory Committee that will take charge in the conduct of a thorough and complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties, thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form by the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II, and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer to maintain complete, accurate and updated PPE Ledgers and Property Cards, respectively; and

For both officers to reconcile the results of the physical inventory with the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards maintained by their respective offices and to affect the necessary adjustments for any discrepancy noted;

We reiterated prior year’s recommendations that Management:

Create a Road Inventory Committee together with the Municipal Assessor and Municipal Accountant to ascertain the cost of each road component including its lot component, if readily available. Otherwise, the fair market value (assessed value) of the lot component and replacement cost of the other components shall be specified;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to properly recognize the value of the lot component in the books of accounts and provide the depreciation cost for each depreciable road component in accordance to COA Circular No. 2015-008;

Direct the Inventory Committee to use the proper format of the RPCLRN with complete details such as road ID, components, cost, and condition; and

Direct the MEO to provide the Inventory Committee and the GSO to be designated relevant data on the road network inventory and local road map of the Municipality.

We further recommended that the LCE enjoin all the Department Heads concerned (Municipal Accountant, GSO and Municipal Engineer) to adopt the relevant guidelines in the LRAMM by the DILG and attend trainings relative to it if there’s any, to be able to adopt and follow the procedures set forth therein and eventual compliance with the requirements thereof on reporting as prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008.

We recommended that management instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to:

Require all collecting officers to prepare RCDs at the close of each business day and effect remittance of their collections daily to the Liquidating Officer. In the case of the deputized collectors in the barangays, require their remittance at least once a month or as soon as the collections reaches the threshold of 5,000.00;

Require the Liquidating Officer to verify the RCDs submitted by the collectors and prepare the RCDs of the said remittances and deposit the same to the depository bank daily or the next banking day;

Require the Liquidating Officer to check the Statement of Accountable Forms as to initial balances on hand, receipts, issues and the ending balances on hand, make physical count of accountable forms remaining in the custody of collectors and check the same against new balances on hand column. Henceforth, accountable forms shall be issued only to those accountable officers who have religiously and completely remitted their collections in compliance with the provisions of Section 30 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I; and

Require all the Accountable Officers with unaccounted accountable forms to formally render a report thereon. In the event that these can no longer be located/presented, a request for relief from accountability for the loss of accountable forms shall be made in accordance with the requirements under COA Circular No. 84-233 dated August 2, 1984.

We recommended that Management;

Prepare the quarterly report on the utilization and status of program/project implementation using the prescribed format (Annex C of LBC No. 151) and post the report in at least 3 conspicuous public places in the locality and on the LGUs website within 20 calendar days from the end of each quarter in consonance with section; and

Send a written notice to the Secretary of DBM, Secretary of DILG, Chairperson of the NTF-ELCAC, coursed through the NTF-ELCAC Vice-Chairperson and RTF-ELCAC concerned. Speaker of the House of Representatives, President of the Senate of the Philippines, and the Chairpersons of the House Committee on Appropriations and Senate Committee on Finance upon posting of the reports on the LGU's website.

We recommended that Management:

Augment the staff who will be in charge of the monthly remittances mandated by law, analysis and reconciliation of the prior year GSIS billings and remittances and cause the immediate remittances of the determined unremitted contributions and loan amortization due to GSIS in compliance with the related laws to avoid unnecessary accumulation of interest and penalties;

Cause the immediate submission of the updated information of the agency and its employees to the GSIS reflecting the updated salaries and status of the employees.

We recommended that Management: 

Adopt the recommended procedural flowchart in the procurement and distribution of food supplies (Annex 6) pursuant to the afore-cited law and regulations, taking into consideration the lack of personnel in the LGU.  

The following are the recommended changes in the procedures:

The Local Chief Executive expedite the recruitment and hiring of a full-time and qualified General Services Officer (GSO);

The inspection of deliveries of food supplies purchased shall be conducted by the personnel presently assigned as inspector and shall be accepted in the Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR), prepared in two copies, by the MSWDO, in the meantime that there is no full-time GSO. The MSWDO shall then keep the second copy of the report for recording in the stock cards while the first copy shall be forwarded to the Municipal Accountant, together with the Delivery Receipt/Sales Invoice, for recording in the books of accounts and subsidiary records; 

On a weekly or monthly basis, the MSWDO shall promptly prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), based on the RIS for the distributed supplies, which shall be submitted to the Municipal Accountant, together with the Accountant’s copy of the RIS, for recording;

The Municipal Accountant and MSWDO shall regularly reconcile their respective records to determine any errors in recording of food supplies procurement, issuances and balances;

The BAC shall evaluate the APP and determine the applicable mode of procurement for each goods or services to be procured contained therein.  After evaluation, the BAC shall issue a Resolution recommending the modes of procurement for all the items to be procured and forwards the same, together with the APP, to the Mayor for approval;  

A copy of the BAC Resolution, together with the approved APP, shall be furnished each Department as basis for the preparation of Purchase Request on goods or services needed for the quarter at the beginning of the year and of each subsequent quarter.

We recommended that Management:

Adopt prescribed control procedures in the receipt, inventory and issuance of donations- in kind, and record the proper cost of the ending inventory based on the value declared by the donor, if available, or using the prevailing market price of the donated items in the books or in the registries, as applicable;

Require the concerned offices/units to properly categorize the Donations- in Kind received by the Municipality and intended for COVID-19 response and other calamities reported in the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances for consolidation;

Require the MDRRMO to submit a consolidated report on Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances, separately for Cash and In-Kind transactions for CY 2020 and onwards, to the NDRRMC through the OCD, copy furnished the Auditor, as required in COA Circular 2014-002 and 2020-009;

Require the assigned staff in Office of the Mayor to maintain Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM to properly account for the ending inventory balances; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements information pertaining to DRRM not evident on the face of the financial statements;

We recommended, and the management agreed, that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant to:

enforce the immediate liquidation of the unliquidated cash advances;

send demand letters requiring the employees concerned to immediately liquidate/settle the long outstanding cash advances especially on the above-mentioned prepayments for travel and those granted to former SDOs; 

withhold the salaries of the accountable officers who are still connected with the City, and not defer the liquidation of cash advances until retirement of employees concerned;

refrain from granting cash advance to undesignated SDOs; and assign a staff to monitor closely and facilitate the liquidation of outstanding cash advances.

We recommended, and the management agreed, that the City Mayor direct the:

a. City Accountant to:

assign two or more personnel focused on the reconciliation of employee’s individual accounts only;

compare the employee’s individual account (EIA) remittances with the amount withheld for each EIA in previous years;

separate the surcharges and penalties charged to employee’s individual accounts to their usual contributions from previous years;

send demand letters to employees with negative balances for their personal contributions or payables; and 

prepare necessary adjusting entries.

b. City Human Resource and Management Officer to:

Notify the GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth of any changes in the employment status of employees such as: promotion, resignation, retirement, or death for proper billing;

Regularly coordinate with the City Accounting Office for the reconciliation of the EIA balances with the amount withheld and remitted.

We recommended, and the management agreed, that the City Mayor direct the:

City Engineer to: 

evaluate the work suspension requests of the contractors as to the appropriateness of the time extension, and duly validate the reasons with the report of the local PAGASA, as the case maybe, and approve requests with valid reasons only in conformity with the provisions of the RIRR of RA No. 9184;

address the issues on Road Right-of-Way, and relocation of informal settlers, and conduct eminent domain proceedings, and facilitate the completion of the 17 incomplete infrastructure projects;

submit complete QRGPPAs, and reports on the actual status of work accomplishments, and ensure the timely implementation of the projects during the budget year;

properly fill out the QRGPPAs form, supplying information for Date Started, and Target Date of Completion, among other;

b. City Planning and Development Officer and City Engineer to:

address issues such as Road Right-of-Way and viability of the project sites during the feasibility or preliminary engineering study, procurement planning, and preliminary design and construction studies, among others, before project implementation in accordance with the RIRR of RA No. 9184.  These problems should be disclosed during the planning stage and extensively discussed when deliberations for the project’s implementation are conducted with the city officials to avoid delay in the implementation of the projects; and

review and investigate the extended implementation of the eighteen infrastructure projects and impose liquidated damages, if warranted.

Bids and Awards Committee should not bid, and most importantly, should not award contracts for infrastructure projects without properly conducting sufficient detailed engineering investigations, surveys and designs, which includes settlements of Road Right-of-Way problems.

We recommended, and the management agreed, that the City Mayor direct the City DRRM Officer to: 

ensure and expedite the implementation of identified PPAs, to strengthen the agency’s capacity in mitigating and preparing for, responding to and recovering from the impact of disasters;

refrain from utilizing portions of the fund for non-disaster related programs, projects and activities;

ensure that all disbursements were supported with complete supporting documents; and

ensure the correctness on the preparation of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRM Fund to provide reliable data.

We recommended, and the management agreed, that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant to:

stop the grant of overtime pay to personnel above SG 23;

observe one-hour breaks for breakfast, lunch, supper or rest, or every after three hours of continuous work;

check the DTR properly if the employee is not tardy or undertime;

provide CTO to employees who exceed the 12 hours maximum limit instead of overtime pay;

check the number of hours rendered on the working day if it meets the required 40 hours of work a week before entitlement and payment of overtime pay to city employees; and

stop the payment of overtime pay to Job Order personnel.

We recommended, and the management agreed, that the City Mayor direct the:

Appraisal Committee to furnish GSO and COA copies of the Appraisal Report and checklist for unserviceable equipment;

GSO to properly fill out the IIRUP, providing information on the description of the assets, date of acquisition, and carrying amount, among others; and submit a corrected copy of the IIRUP, taking into consideration the deficiencies noted in audit;


Appraisal Committee and GSO to recheck and verify the Appraisal Process, ensuring that the guidelines were complied with, to validate the appropriateness of the appraised values of the unserviceable properties.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the: 

Inventory Committee/Property Custodian to:

Formulate plans and strategize the complete conduct of physical count of all its PPE, and prepare and submit the RPCPPE not later than January 31 of the ensuing year in compliance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I; 

Reconcile the RPCPPE with the records of the City Accountant; 

Ensure the report’s usability by including all the required information in the RPCPPE;

c. City Accountant to:

Reconcile accounting records with the RPCPPE;

Coordinate with the City Engineer to determine the road network to be derecognized, then drop from the books the cost and the related accumulated depreciation of the subject Road Network account;

Determine the cost of the donated parcel of lands and prepare an adjusting journal entry;

Record the receipt of the donated and exchanged parcel of lands in the books of the City; and

Coordinate with the GSO and Custodian of the Land Titles of the City to take effect unrecorded donations; 

We recommended further that the City Mayor create an Inventory Committee, who will be temporarily relieved from all their regular duties, to complete the physical inventory in three (3) months or less, and to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities; and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular 2020-006.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the: 

City Accountant and City Treasurer to stop the grant of cash advances for procurement activities that should be undertaken through the appropriate mode of procurement provided under RA No. 9184;

BAC Chairman and CHO to prepare and submit the requirements of GPPB Circular No. 02-2021 in the future procurement of ancillary supplies;

Direct the BAC and end-user/ implementing office to undertake only procurement activities in accordance with approved APP, and revise/update the plan, if necessary, to include items not considered in the original plan; and

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Direct the City DRRM Officer to:

procure equipment, tools, and supplies as provided under COA Memorandum No. 2012-73;

judiciously prepare the AIP for LDRRMF, using the prescribed format, incorporating time schedules, availability of resources and other contingencies to avoid delay in the implementation of PPAs;

ensure and expedite the implementation of identified PPAs, to strengthen the agency’s capacity in mitigating and preparing for, responding to and recovering from the impact of disasters; and

The City Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting entries to record the unexpended DRRM Fund for QRF and MOOE, and unrecorded donated property; and ensure the completeness of the supporting documents;


a. The CDRRMO to: 

The City Treasurer to ensure that supporting documents are available and attached to the Disbursement Vouchers before the issuance of check.

We recommended and Management agreed, that the City Mayor:

a. Require the General Services Office to:

Secure TCT to support the ownership of the land;

Provide staff and equipment to GSO Personnel concerned in securing and filing of TCT and other documents;

Reconcile records with the Accounting Office;

Update and submit PCs; and

b. Require the City Accountant to:

Reconcile the records with the GSO;

c. Require the Inventory Committee to:

Measure the fair market value or appraisal value of PPE without acquisition cost; and

Ensure the full implementation of “one-time cleansing of PPE.”

We recommended that management adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of the PPE account of the LGU, specifically, the following:

A. The Inventory Committee:

a. Ensure that the physical count is recorded/documented daily in a standard Inventory Count Form (ICF), using the format in Annex A of this Circular, which shall be used as the basis in the preparation of the RPCPPE after the physical count;

c. Prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) covering all the PPEs of the LGU;

B. Property and Accounting Unit

a. The Property and Accounting Units shall undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled. The reconciliation shall be completed within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee.

We recommended that management strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular 2020-006 on the one-time cleansing of the PPE accounts of the Municipality, specifically, the following:

A. Local Chief Executive:

To temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee from all their regular duties to be able to complete the physical inventory of all PPEs of the LGU in due times.

Direct the Property Unit, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, to prepare a PIP containing at least the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, the cut-off date and a schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;

B. The Inventory Committee:

Conduct a complete physical count of PPE based on the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

Ensure that the physical count is recorded/documented daily in a standard Inventory Count Form (ICF), using the format in Annex A of this Circular, which shall be used as the basis in the preparation of the RPCPPE after the physical count;

Prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) covering all the PPEs of the LGU;

Prepare and update Property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconciled with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the LGU's PPEs;

C. Property and Accounting unit

The Property and Accounting Units shall undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled. The reconciliation shall be completed within ten (10) days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit promptly the required monthly and quarterly financial reports on or before the due dates in compliance with Item 4.1 of COA Circular No. 2010-001 dated March 2, 2010;
Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timelines of the abovementioned law, rules, and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accounting Office all the disbursement vouchers, payrolls, and official receipts, including the corresponding reports for each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timeliness of the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor within ten days of the ensuing month; and
To address the issue of lack of manpower by filling up the vacant Plantilla in various offices or hiring temporary workers to assist with urgent backlogs and daily tasks.

Considering the several unimplemented projects from the 20 per cent DF, we recommended the following:
Prior years’ PPAs for Municipal Aid to Barangays be directly implemented by the MGG;
Collective efforts are enjoined to study the status of all PPAs that need to be implemented so that the best strategies may be determined, setbacks are avoided, and implementation can run smoothly and expeditiously;
Planning be made meticulously so that priority and more feasible PPAs are identified, budgets are sufficiently appropriated, realignments are avoided, and the period of implementation is realistic; and
Exert efforts in the implementation of all unimplemented PPAs and ensure that at the end of the succeeding year, unimplemented projects are diminished, if not all finished.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE:
Require the HR to assess the existing Organizational Structure, expedite filling up the vacant positions through advertisement and assessment of qualified employees for promotion, and submit a report thereon to the LCE for approval by the appropriate bodies;
Make written policy/guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring JO workers, who should not perform tasks assigned to existing permanent and regular employees per their job descriptions;
Limit the hiring/deployment to those offices that are extremely in need of their services; and
Incorporate in the JO contract the number of man hours, quantity, and duration of the work to be performed by the JO personnel and require them to submit quantified accomplishment reports and signed copies of contracts to support payment of wages.

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timelines of the abovementioned law, rules, and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accounting Office all the disbursement vouchers, payrolls, and official receipts, including the corresponding reports for each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timeliness on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor within ten days of the ensuing month;
To address the issue of lack of manpower by filling up the vacant Plantilla in various offices or hiring temporary workers to assist with urgent backlogs and daily tasks.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the HR to assess the existing Organizational Structure, expedite filling up the vacant positions through advertisement and assessment of qualified employees for promotion, and submit a report thereon to the LCE for approval by appropriate bodies;
Make written policy/guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring JO workers, who should not perform tasks assigned to existing permanent and regular employees per their job descriptions;
Limit the hiring/deployment to those offices that are extremely in need of their services; and
Incorporate in the JO contract the number of man hours, quantity, and duration of the work to be performed by the JO personnel and require them to submit quantified accomplishment reports and signed copies of contracts to support payment of wages.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Establish an Inventory Committee with an adequate number of members and require them, together with the Head of Property and Accounting Units, to undergo the necessary training to complete the physical inventory in line with the One-Time Cleansing of PPE;
Prior to the inventory taking, require the Municipal Accounting Office and GSO to submit the updated PPELC and RPCPPE, respectively, to the Inventory Committee to be used as inventory working papers, which shall be the basis for the preparation of the Physical Inventory Plan;
After the physical count, require the Inventory Committee to prepare the RPCPPE in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts and the updated capitalization threshold;
Thereafter, direct the GSO and Municipal Accounting Office to proceed with the reconciliation procedures and subsequent activities such as the disposition and/or derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs and corresponding accounting entries and disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements; and
Direct the GSO to reclassify PPE items costing below ₱50,000, which are still in their custody, to the appropriate semi-expendable property accounts and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Submit the required supporting documents for the claims recorded under the Accounts Payable account, such as Delivery Receipts, Inspection and Acceptance Reports, and Billing Statements, to establish their validity and propriety;
Conduct a detailed review and reconciliation of the beginning balances of Accounts Payable and identify obligations that may have already been paid or no longer valid, and make the appropriate adjusting entries;
Determine the validity of obligations related to the stale checks and issue replacement checks, if warranted; and
Strengthen internal controls by implementing periodic reconciliation procedures and ensuring complete and proper documentation in the recording of payables, in compliance with IPSAS 1 and 19.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct a comprehensive analysis and reconciliation of receivables and payables, and coordinate with concerned offices or agencies for the retrieval of relevant documents to validate the accuracy and legitimacy of the balances;
Assess the collectability of loans receivables and/or initiate immediate collection or settlement efforts, including the issuance of demand letters;
Determine and recommend the appropriate disposition of accounts that are deemed dormant or uncollectible, and prepare the necessary documentation for write-off in accordance with COA Circular No. 2023-008; and
Ensure adequate documentation of transactions in the subsidiary ledgers, and strengthen controls on the regular review and monitoring for all receivable and payable accounts to ensure timely collection, settlement, or adjustment, and to prevent recurrence of similar deficiencies.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the discrepancy of ₱6,360,781.67 and submit the complete subsidiary records;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the appropriate adjusting entries for the increase in capitalization threshold, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2022-004;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to complete the inventory taking, applying the procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Thereafter, instruct the GSO and Municipal Accounting Office to proceed with the reconciliation procedures for the one-time cleansing of PPEs and the subsequent activities such as disposition of non-existing/missing PPEs; derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without an available record of accountability; and preparation of accounting entries and disclosure in the Notes to the Financial Statements;
Submit a request for authority to derecognize the unaccounted balances supported with the necessary documentation, including the items already derecognized in the books;
Require the GSO to prepare property cards for both previously acquired items and items to be acquired, using the RPCPPE as a guide, to record details such as description, acquisition, transfer, disposal, and other relevant information about the PPE, thereby facilitating future reconciliation of property records and promptly resolving any discrepancies identified; and
Direct the GSO to reclassify PPE items costing below ₱50,000 to the appropriate semi-expendable property accounts and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
