Recommendation:
To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
conduct risk assessment;
identify critical processes and functions;
determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

We recommended that the Management require the:

MGSO to render a Report on Local Road Network and keep a complete and updated Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;

Municipal Accountant, Municipal Engineer and GSO prepare the necessary reconciliation to established the correct balance of the Local Road Network for CY2022.

To prepare and submit the Property Inventory Form (PIF) to GIF, GSIS, and to the Auditor, in compliance with COA Circular 2018-002 and, in coordination with the Municipal Engineering Office, ensure that all the insurable properties and assets of the Municipality are included in the said listing;

Ensure that sufficient appropriation is made to cover the Insurance Expense for all insurable properties;

To immediately secure insurance coverage for the buildings and other insurable properties not yet insured from GIF, GSIS; and

To always ensure that the insurance coverage of the insurable properties and assets of the Municipality are promptly renewed every year and that adequate insurance coverage are secured on the assets to provide the Municipality protection and indemnification for any damage caused to the assets due to fire, earthquake, storm or other calamities.

We recommended that Management:

Charge confidential expenses to appropriations for that purpose and properly record the same in the books as Confidential Expenses; 

Stop the practice of paying confidential expenses thru reimbursement. Release confidential funds thru a cash advance duly supported by documents required per Sections 6.1.7 and 6.1.8 and drawn by a duly designated and bonded SDOs or HoA; 

Observe the procedural guidelines outlined under Section 6.2 for the liquidation of the cash advance; and

Observe all other procedural guidelines and reporting requirements contained in DBM -DILG-DND-GCG-COA Joint Circular No. 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015 with respect to the disbursement of confidential funds.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to identify and establish the correct balance of the remaining Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs for each source agency and thereafter:   

Return to the concerned source agencies the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof;

Revert to Government Equity the balances of fund transfers in the nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention of the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws, rules and regulations; 

Retain special purpose funds; and  

Clean the books of accounts, particularly the accounts Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 in order to present fairly the Liability accounts in the financial statements.

We recommend that Management:

Make representations with the NHA and request for possible extension of payment or, if possible, condonation of the loan and delinquent interest;
Appropriate the necessary funds for the repayment of the NHA loan and the delinquent interest thereon to avoid further incurrence of unnecessary expenses like penalties or fines for non-payment of the said loan;

Exert extra effort to locate the supporting documents to determine the legitimacy and propriety of the claims under the PMF and revert to the Unappropriated Surplus of the General Fund the amount of ₱671,704.45, considering that it has been dormant for quite some time;

Conduct periodic review and monitoring of payable accounts so that these accounts will consist only of valid claims against the Municipality; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the Loans Payable-Domestic account as Current and Non-Current Liabilities for better presentation of liabilities of the LGU in the Statement of Financial Position as at the year-end/reporting date.

We recommended the following courses of action:
 The Municipal Accountant send demand letters to the concerned accountable officers (AOs) requesting immediate liquidation of the cash advance or settlement of the amounts due from them; 

 After the lapse of 30 days after receipt by the concerned AO of the demand letter and he/she fails to settle the cash advance or receivable, the Agency Head shall cause the withholding of the payment of any money due the AO;

 The Municipal Accountant should strictly require that the Cash Advances shall be supported with approved payroll or estimate of expenses to support the validity of the transaction, to avoid suspension in audit; and;

 No additional cash advance shall be granted by the Municipal Accountant to officials and/or employees, prior to the liquidation of the previous ones

